Research the design and implementation of infrastructure validation frameworks — the layer of tooling that sits above individual linters and integrates multiple IaC analysis tools into a cohesive quality gate. I am building a validation framework for Kubernetes manifests, Terraform modules, Helm charts, CICD pipelines, Compose files, and GitOps configurations and need to understand how industry-leading frameworks structure their scoring, reporting, and extensibility models.

Cover: how does Polaris (Fairwinds) aggregate multiple Kubernetes checks into a single audit report? What is its scoring model — weighted sum, pass/fail threshold, or something else? How does it handle partial compliance (e.g., a Deployment has resource limits but no security context)?

Research Terraform compliance frameworks: Terraform Sentinel (HashiCorp), OPA/Conftest for Terraform plan JSON, and Terrat/Atlantis policy-as-code integrations. What is the schema of a Terraform plan JSON file and how do tools traverse it to evaluate policies?

Investigate composite scoring approaches for infrastructure security posture. Are there published methodologies for combining scores from multiple tools (e.g., Trivy image scan + Polaris manifest check + Checkov IaC scan) into a single infrastructure health score? How do cloud security posture management (CSPM) tools like Wiz, Orca, and Prisma Cloud approach unified scoring?

Cover the reporting formats used by these tools — SARIF for CI integration, JUnit XML for test runners, custom JSON schemas for dashboards — and research what format is most useful for a developer-facing CLI tool that needs to surface actionable remediation guidance alongside findings.
